        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Polish PM Donald Tusk survived a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-12-jun-25-spotlight-h1-1-parliamentary-confidence-vote?source=website" target="_blank">parliamentary confidence vote</a>. The vote was meant to reaffirm his leadership as Tusk-backed Rafal Trzaskowski lost the presidential election to right-wing Karol Nawrocki. He emphasized that speculation about his governmentâ€™s downfall was undermining its ability to function. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Meanwhile, Tuskâ€™s reform agenda, including reversing controversial judicial changes and expanding abortion rights, faces challenges due to presidential vetoes. However, Nawrocki, similarly to outgoing President Andrzej Duda, is likely to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-12-jun-25-spotlight-h1-2-block-key-initiatives?source=website" target="_blank">block key initiatives</a>. Tusk's critics say this government has made little progress since he took office in December 2023.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
        Tusk called the confidence vote an opening and plans a cabinet reshuffle in July. Still, the opposition argues that his presidential loss may have sealed his political fate, raising doubts about his ability to govern effectively amid rising tensions. </p>
